    <a title="Kristy Miller" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6915394-kristy-miller"><img alt="Kristy Miller" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471835134p2/6915394.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1161275535?book_show_action=true">Jan 08, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kristy Miller" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kristy Miller" href="/user/show/6915394-kristy-miller">Kristy Miller</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6915394-kristy-miller?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6915394-kristy-miller?shelf=film-adaptation">film-adaptation</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6915394-kristy-miller?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6915394-kristy-miller?shelf=social-cultural-studies">social-cultural-studies</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1161275535" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7613104850867761861">I don&apos;t know where to begin with this book. To say it is about the painting of Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I by Gustav Klimt is an massive understatement. It is so much more than that!<br/><br/>This book starts by bouncing between the lives of Gustav and Adele until they meet at the turn of the 20th century. But we don&apos;t just get a biography of these two and the relationship that would last the rest of their lives. We are treated to a glimpse of belle epoque Vienna in all it&apos;s glory. Gustav and Adele&apos;s </span>
  <span id="freeText7613104850867761861" style="display:none">I don't know where to begin with this book. To say it is about the painting of Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I by Gustav Klimt is an massive understatement. It is so much more than that!<br /><br />This book starts by bouncing between the lives of Gustav and Adele until they meet at the turn of the 20th century. But we don't just get a biography of these two and the relationship that would last the rest of their lives. We are treated to a glimpse of belle epoque Vienna in all it's glory. Gustav and Adele's circles were filled with the who's who of music, art, literature, and philosophy of middle Europe. In this world aristocratic Christians socialized and intermarried with the rising Jewish aristocracy without thought. Klimt died in 1918, and died Adele seven years later. She left a note asking her husband Ferdinand, who had commissioned two portraits of his wife by the man who likely cuckolded him, to leave her Klimts to the Austrian museums. We then enter the era of Nazi power in Austria, and Austria's complicity in the systematic robbery, blackmailing, and murder of it's Jewish citizens. When Ferdinand was forced to flee Austria for Switzerland his portrait of his beloved wife ended up at the Belevedere Museum in Vienna. To hide it's Jewishness it was renamed "Dame in Gold." As we proceed through the war, the author returns to the many friends of Adele and Gustav, and we learn their fates, the fates of their children, and the fates of the great art they created. The final part of the book explains how former Nazi bureaucrats covered up the massive theft of culture that had occurred in the last 10 years. The children of the collaborators began to uncover the secrets, of their parents and this opened the door for Maria Altman, Adele Bloch-Bauer's niece, to make a claim on her aunt's portrait.<br /><br />This is more than art history, more than biography, more than historical account. It is all of those things, as well as a sociological study of willful ignorance and amnesia. Vienna wanted to forget it's complicity in WWII. After the war Austria tried to claim itself as Hitler's first victim, but it's hard to do since not even a token resistance was made. Hitler was greeted with flowers, and Austrians quickly turned on Jewish friends and family members. After the war they still celebrated "heroes" that had fought for Germany, and denied exit passes for art that had been looted, and was considered valuable. Heirs were forced to sell iconic pieces at greatly reduced prices in exchange for visas for lesser works. The provenance of pieces became murky, at best. There is so much information in this book. It was utterly fascinating. Yes, there were many people in play, but the author took care to remind you who someone was and how they related to the major players. I've never particularly cared for Klimt but now that I know the stories of these paintings, and what happened to these vibrant and interesting women, I will never look at these works the same way again.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7613104850867761861" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


